  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>A score of 6 at ICLR doesn't mean the same thing as a score of 6 at AAAI. Reviewers at different venues have different score baselines, different thresholds for what counts as a fatal flaw, and different unwritten criteria that never appear in the official reviewer guidelines. If you get a review back and don't know the venue's calibration, you're reading a number without a scale.</p>

  <h2>What I built</h2>
  <p>PaperScope fetches real peer review data from 35 venue-years across ML, NLP, and vision conferences via the OpenReview API — ICLR, NeurIPS, ICML, CVPR, ACL, AAAI, KDD, and more, spanning 2023 through 2026. From that I built detailed calibration references for the four biggest families — ICLR, NeurIPS, ICML/TMLR, and CVPR/ICCV/ECCV — covering real score distributions, accept/reject language patterns, and the hidden criteria that consistently show up in negative decisions but never make it into official guidelines. The rest of the fetched venues are queued but don't have a compiled reference yet. I packaged the finished references as a Claude Code skill so you can ask Claude to review a paper and get feedback grounded in real venue-specific context instead of generic AI commentary.</p>

  <h2>What I found</h2>
  <p>The score scales themselves aren't even comparable across venues — CVPR's 1–6 scale and ICLR's 1–10 scale don't line up the way you'd assume; a 3 at CVPR is roughly equivalent to a 5 at NeurIPS, not a 3. Acceptance rates vary too (ICLR runs around 32% versus CVPR's 23–25%), and each venue has its own unwritten rules — ICLR reviewers, for instance, explicitly penalize unnecessary complexity in a way no official guideline states. The most useful output of the project wasn't the score distributions themselves but the language calibration — the specific phrases that reliably predict rejection or acceptance at a given venue tell you more than the raw number ever could.</p>